      <hedline>
        <hl1>Pollution for Sale</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Prof Paul L Joskow letter says emissions cap and trading program established by 1990 acid rain law provides mechanism through which government can reduce sulfur dioxide emissions below caps in law (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Acid Rain's National Reach'' (editorial, April 10): The emissions cap and trading program established by the 1990 acid rain law provides a mechanism through which the Federal Government (or any state government, organization or individual) can reduce sulfur dioxide emissions below the caps provided for in the laws.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Acid Rain's National Reach'' (editorial, April 10): The emissions cap and trading program established by the 1990 acid rain law provides a mechanism through which the Federal Government (or any state government, organization or individual) can reduce sulfur dioxide emissions below the caps provided for in the laws.</p>
        <p>By simply buying and retiring sulfur dioxide permits, which give the holder the right to emit one ton of sulfur dioxide, anyone can keep them from being used to support future emissions. These permits are readily available in the private market and cost about $200.</p>
        <p>Among other benefits, this approach will force the Federal Government to recognize the costs of tightening the cap on sulfur dioxide emissions, since it will have to finance the costs of buying and retiring emissions permits.</p>
        <p>PAUL L. JOSKOW  Cambridge, Mass., April 11, 1999</p>
        <p>The writer is an economics professor, Massachusetts Institute of Technology.</p>
      </block>
